<p><b>Humanistic psychology</b> is a school of psychology that emerged in the 1950s in reaction to both <a href="/wiki/Behaviorism" title="Behaviorism">behaviorism</a> and <a href="/wiki/Psychoanalysis" title="Psychoanalysis">psychoanalysis</a>. It is explicitly concerned with the human dimension of psychology and the human context for the development of psychological theory.</p>
